    realWorld: String.raw`<p>ISI is the reason high-speed wireline links look the way they do. A $56$ Gbit/s PAM-4 SerDes lane driving a metre of backplane is operating where the channel's insertion loss at the Nyquist frequency can exceed $30$ dB, so the received eye is not merely degraded but <strong>completely closed</strong> — peak distortion well above $1$, an eye a scope cannot even display without help. The link works anyway, because the receiver rebuilds the eye: continuous-time linear equalization boosts the high frequencies the trace attenuated, a feed-forward equalizer at the transmitter pre-distorts the waveform so the channel's own response flattens it, and a decision-feedback equalizer cancels post-cursor ISI from already-decided symbols without the noise enhancement a purely linear inverse would incur. Every one of those blocks exists because of the taps $h(nT)$, and the industry's test methodology is built around the same quantities: eye height and width, which are $2|h(0)|(1-D)$ and the timing margin, are the pass/fail criteria in the standards. The same story plays out in DSL, where a twisted pair kilometres long is grotesquely dispersive and the answer was to abandon single-carrier signalling entirely in favour of discrete multitone — OFDM by another name — with a cyclic prefix absorbing the channel's memory and a per-subcarrier bit-loading that assigns more bits where the channel is strong and fewer in the nulls the equalizer would otherwise have to fight. Optical long-haul links tell the same story in a different medium: chromatic dispersion and polarisation-mode dispersion spread pulses across many symbol periods, and modern coherent receivers correct it with digital filters that are, mathematically, exactly the equalizers in this topic's table.</p>
<p>In wireless, ISI decided an entire generation of architecture. GSM ran at about $271$ ksym/s, giving $T\approx3.7\ \mu$s against urban delay spreads of $1$–$3\ \mu$s: a ratio near unity, squarely in the ISI-limited regime, with a channel memory of a few symbols. That was small enough for a Viterbi equalizer, and GSM receivers duly carried one, using the midamble training sequence embedded in every burst to estimate the channel taps before running MLSE over the trellis. When the industry moved to LTE and 5G NR at bandwidths of $20$ MHz and beyond, the symbol period collapsed and the channel memory grew into the tens of taps — an $M^{L}$ trellis is simply not payable — so the question changed from "how do we equalize this?" to "how do we not have to?" The answer was OFDM: subcarrier spacings of $15$ kHz (LTE) or $15\times2^{\mu}$ kHz (NR) give useful symbol durations of tens of microseconds, dwarfing the delay spread, and a cyclic prefix of around $4.7\ \mu$s absorbs the residual overlap so that equalization is one complex multiply per subcarrier. The Nyquist criterion is still visible in the same standards from the other direction, too: the OFDM subcarriers themselves are spaced at exactly $1/T_u$ so that each completes a whole number of cycles in the receiver's FFT window, which is why frequency offset is so damaging — it breaks that orthogonality and converts a clean subcarrier grid into mutual interference, the frequency-domain cousin of the timing-offset problem that reopens ISI in a nominally Nyquist pulse.</p>`,
    related: ['pulse-shaping', 'rrc-filter', 'eye-diagram', 'nyquist-sampling', 'ber']
